One of my favorite warm ups before squatting is to use a band for some slow bodyweight squats. I'll often throw a 1-1/2 motion into the mix. The goal with this exercise is to get your hips engaged equally on both sides before getting under the barbell. If you don't have symmetrical engagement in your hips you'll often see twists or shifts when lifting.📝
.
Tag a friend below who could use this warm up the next time they squat👇🏼

The traditional medical model will try to look at a scan of your back and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. However, there is a ton of research that shows just because you find a problem on MRI does not mean it’s the exact cause of pain. 
.
So what do we do?  We fit your symptoms into a movement diagnosis category! This is something I learned from renowned back expert @backfitpro. A movement diagnosis tells you what motions, postures and loads to avoid in the short term so we don’t continue your pain. It doesn’t matter how many corrective exercises or stability drills you do, if you continue to push into your trigger for pain, it usually won’t get better on it’s own. 
.
The process of limiting individual movement triggers has been shown in research to help reduce pain effectively. It’s not creating fear of movement but rather empowering you to understand your injury so you can take control of the rehab process. 
.
Shout out to @krispy_kremez for being my patient model in this video!

One method to help fix a hip shift when squatting is to use a band around the hips, attempting to pull the lifter into more shift. Doing so creates a reaction in the body that can help some find better balance like this young powerlifter who came to me with hip pain. 
.
1️⃣If you’re dealing with a hip shift, be sure to also check out my YouTube video “how to fix a hip shift” and try the mobility test I share there as well!
2️⃣If you’d like to see the longer version of my work with this young powerlifter @tate.fegley, check out my YouTube video “11 year old powerlifter fixes injury & crushes big weight.”

This is a novel exercise to help enhance shoulder stability when lifting overhead - something I first learned from @benlustigphysiotherapy. I’ve used it many times in the past half year with patients of mine recovering from shoulder pain who need more stability when lifting overhead and have seen tremendous improvements.

When to use: be sure to try the test I showed in this video first!!!! If you’re weak - then try & retest to see if this is helpful for you. Remember, “corrective exercises” are only helpful if used in the right situation. Never do an exercise just because it looks cool on social media.😉
.

During Luke’s injury rehab with me, we ran into a pretty significant limitation in ankle mobility. Now we were definitely seeing some progress with banded joint mobilizations, stretching and soft tissue work with rolling, but he was still a little off balance in his bottom squat position.📝
.
Now when I see problems like this – we often look at the ankle joint  especially the motion of knee moving over the toe – a motion called dorsiflexion – but we need to also look at the motions that occur in other planes like rotation and glide.✅
.
I assessed his lateral shin motion with this movement. Clearly very different on his injury side. This prompted me to test his tibial rotation and as you can see he has much less rotation on his injured side.📝
.
I suggested he use this banded drill. With the band placed under the base of his 1st toe, he tensioned the band and drove his knee out to the side – feeling his glutes working hard and held for 10”. Now if you don’t keep a stable foot during this motion the band will snap out from under your foot.❌ .
We also worked on trying to improve lateral tibial glide, holding the foot down in place and pushing the knee to the side and holding for a few seconds. After performing those you can see a huge difference in ankle mobility.🙌🏼 .
So the next week when we were squatting, I noted he was a little off balance in his bottom position – with the bar shooting out over his toes. We did one more set of tibial rotation drills and the very next see you can see a large difference – now more balanced and able to sit down with the bar over his mid foot.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @thelukemeredith for putting in the hard work during rehab, you're doing such great work man. Also thank you to @3d4medical with the compete anatomy app for the visual of the body today. .

Creating sufficient stability/tension in the body & activating the hips BEFORE the bar is moved from the ground is key during the execution of a deadlift for optimal performance. Learning this set up is also a very important part of the rehab process when returning from back pain (like @superchuckcw is shown here performing). This is because many who develop back pain when deadlifting have very strong backs but fail to control the strength they do have and coordinate it with the hips. 
.
These tips are things I have picked up from giants who have come before me like @eddycoan, @briancarroll1306 & @backfitpro. 
.
To see the full back pain evaluation & treatment of  @superchuckcw - check out my most recent YouTube video!📲

Is it okay to round? This clip is from a recent SquatU podcast with guests @eddycoan & @backfitpro. In this clip we discussed a specific picture of Ed that some use to justify back round MOVEMENT of the spine when deadlifting. Notice we are not discussing a gradual round that is locked in place. The goal is to lock the spine in place and try to limit motion of it as much as possible when we pull weight from the ground. 
.
Hope you enjoyed this clip. If you would like to see the full video of our discussion, check out the Squat University youtube channel or you can listen to the full podcast on any podcast platform!

So you just finished some heavy squats…what do you do next? One of my favorite assistant exercises is the single leg RDL performed with a barbell or a kettlebell in one hand…but what if this is too difficult?🤔
.
Let’s regress back to a more simple version of the single leg movement with shoes off to work balance and coordination. Grab the ground with your foot, big toe jammed down. Brace your core and kick your heel back as you tip forward entirely about the hip. Hold for a few seconds before coming back up. From the front view, keep your free leg toe pointed down and don’t allow the hips to rotate or the knee to shift in.❌
.
If you find yourself showing the common fault of dropping the chest and not having that stable connection with the back leg, grab a band and loop it from heel to shoulder. Maintain the tension on the band as you then perform the movement again. This physical cue can assist in helping you maintain the desired connection between the lower and upper body, allowing you to hinge and move about the hips.✅
.
Eventually you can add weight, like I’m showing here with a kettlebell.🙌🏼
.
Shout out to @tank_murakami for being today’s athlete model at the start, to @eleikosport for the barbell set seen in the first RDL clip & @kettlebellkings for the weight used in the 2nd clip🙏🏼

.
The amazing olympians that competed this past week didn’t start lifting huge weight at the beginning. They all started with just the barbell too!

It doesn’t matter where you’re currently at - it’s about starting & working each day to get 1% better!

When you squat stack your back in a stable position aligning your ribs and pelvis- and maintaining that posture during the full lift. Here’s why this is important. Place your thumbs just to the side of your abs and take a big breath into your stomach & notice the expansion. This is how we breathe for optimal stability before lifting. Now if you assume this over extended back fault, Try that same test with that posture and notice how you’ll be unable to “fill the tank” as much meaning this posture is not optimal for creating stability. 
.

node.text:
When you set up in a clean or snatch, turn your elbows out to the sides. This internally rotated position of the shoulder does 2 things. First it helps you engage your lats (remember these muscles extend and internally rotate the arms). Second, you’ll have a better shot at keeping the bar close to your body during the pull. If the elbows turn back behind you (more of an externally rotated position) it’s easier for the barbell to loop away from the body.
.
Now, as the bar moves overhead (as in the snatch) or to the front rack position (as in the clean) the shoulders then move into an externally rotated position BUT both lifts will start with relative internal rotation.
.
Any questions?
.
Shout out to @darrenbarnes56 for being my athlete model for this post.

One of my favorite warm ups before squatting is to use a band for some slow bodyweight squats. I'll often throw a 1-1/2 motion into the mix. The goal with this exercise is to get your hips engaged equally on both sides before getting under the barbell. If you don't have symmetrical engagement in your hips you'll often see twists or shifts when lifting.📝
.

Before you start adding weight to the bar, we want to ensure optimal mobility in both our hips. Large differences in mobility can lead to problems in technique & increase risk of injury over time. Assessing & fixing small imbalances don’t always have to be complicated. Just sitting in a deep squat like I show today and opening your hip as far as possible without your foot rolling on its side can be a quick way to assess mobility. If one side is more stiff, trying some isometric squeezes to open the hip up in the extreme position of the deep squat can help improve this mobility!
.
Any questions?
.
Shout out to @max_lang_weightlifting for being my athlete model at the start of this video.🙏🏼

The traditional medical model will try to look at a scan of your back and determine what they see as “abnormal” to be the exact cause of pain. However, there is a ton of research that shows just because you find a problem on MRI does not mean it’s the exact cause of pain. 
.
So what do we do?  We fit your symptoms into a movement diagnosis category! This is something I learned from renowned back expert @backfitpro. A movement diagnosis tells you what motions, postures and loads to avoid in the short term so we don’t continue your pain. It doesn’t matter how many corrective exercises or stability drills you do, if you continue to push into your trigger for pain, it usually won’t get better on it’s own. 
.
The process of limiting individual movement triggers has been shown in research to help reduce pain effectively. It’s not creating fear of movement but rather empowering you to understand your injury so you can take control of the rehab process. 
.
Shout out to @krispy_kremez for being my patient model in this video!

Excellent example of proper breathing mechanics from Tian Tao. Too many think breathing “into your stomach” means to push your belly forward. This is incorrect. You want to “fill the tank” and example fully in a 360 degree manner. Trying to breathe “into your lateral obliques” is a cue that helps some feel for this proper breathing (called a diaphragmatic breath).
.
